        <!-- ================= GLOSSARY TAB ================= -->
        <div id="panel-glossary" class="hidden space-y-6">
            <div class="bg-slate-800/80 border border-slate-700/60 rounded-xl p-6">
                <h2 class="text-lg font-bold text-indigo-400 mb-2">Network Address Translation Terminology</h2>
                <p class="text-sm text-slate-400 mb-6">Learn the precise industry definitions required to analyze packet flow patterns and configure corporate networking gateways.</p>
                
                <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
                    <!-- Term 1 -->
                    <div class="bg-slate-900 p-4 rounded-xl border border-slate-800 hover:border-slate-700 transition">
                        <h3 class="text-sm font-bold text-emerald-400 font-mono mb-1">Inside Local IP</h3>
                        <p class="text-xs text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">
                            The IP address assigned to a host on the local (private) network. These addresses are defined in RFC 1918 (e.g., <code class="bg-slate-800 px-1 py-0.5 rounded font-mono text-indigo-300">192.168.x.x</code>, <code class="bg-slate-800 px-1 py-0.5 rounded font-mono text-indigo-300">10.x.x.x</code>) and are not routable across the public internet.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <!-- Term 2 -->
                    <div class="bg-slate-900 p-4 rounded-xl border border-slate-800 hover:border-slate-700 transition">
                        <h3 class="text-sm font-bold text-emerald-400 font-mono mb-1">Inside Global IP</h3>
                        <p class="text-xs text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">
                            The public, globally routable IP address registered to the router's external interface (WAN) facing the internet. This is the shared mask used to represent local devices to the outside world.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <!-- Term 3 -->
                    <div class="bg-slate-900 p-4 rounded-xl border border-slate-800 hover:border-slate-700 transition">
                        <h3 class="text-sm font-bold text-emerald-400 font-mono mb-1">Outside Global IP</h3>
                        <p class="text-xs text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">
                            The public, routable IP address assigned to a destination host on the internet, such as a web server (<code class="bg-slate-800 px-1 py-0.5 rounded font-mono text-indigo-300">93.184.216.34</code>) or cloud database.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <!-- Term 4 -->
                    <div class="bg-slate-900 p-4 rounded-xl border border-slate-800 hover:border-slate-700 transition">
                        <h3 class="text-sm font-bold text-emerald-400 font-mono mb-1">Port Address Translation (PAT)</h3>
                        <p class="text-xs text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">
                            Sometimes called <em>NAT Overload</em>. A design variant of NAT where multiple internal devices share a single Public IP address. The router tracks sessions by appending distinct <strong>source port numbers</strong> to distinguish individual data flows.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <!-- Term 5 -->
                    <div class="bg-slate-900 p-4 rounded-xl border border-slate-800 hover:border-slate-700 transition">
                        <h3 class="text-sm font-bold text-emerald-400 font-mono mb-1">Stateful Inspection / Mapping</h3>
                        <p class="text-xs text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">
                            The process where a router registers mappings in an internal registry (NAT Table) for an outbound request. This registry is inspected when packets return from the internet to guarantee they are delivered back to the correct internal client.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <!-- Term 6 -->
                    <div class="bg-slate-900 p-4 rounded-xl border border-slate-800 hover:border-slate-700 transition">
                        <h3 class="text-sm font-bold text-emerald-400 font-mono mb-1">RFC 1918 Address Space</h3>
                        <p class="text-xs text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">
                            The formal specification defining standard IP blocks reserved strictly for private local networks: <code class="bg-slate-800 px-1 py-0.5 rounded font-mono text-indigo-300">10.0.0.0/8</code>, <code class="bg-slate-800 px-1 py-0.5 rounded font-mono text-indigo-300">172.16.0.0/12</code>, and <code class="bg-slate-800 px-1 py-0.5 rounded font-mono text-indigo-300">192.168.0.0/16</code>.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
